MartineRothblatt:Mother,CEO,andMore





Catherine Hua




                  almost 2 years

                    

                    Philadelphia, PA, United States

                    
Story

































 











Header image credit to nypost.com.
In May this year, Forbes released its list of the 50 Richest Self-Made Women. The 35th richest woman on the list, Martine Rothblatt, pulls in a net worth of $390 million dollars with her beginnings as founder of Sirius Satellite Radio in 1990 after graduating from UCLA with a joint MBA/PhD degree in 1981. When Jenesis, one of her four daughters, developed the rare disease pulmonary arterial hypertension, she left Sirius to become founder, Chairwoman and CEO of United Therapeutics Corporation to help find treatments. Since then, she has remained with the biotech firm, which now sells four drugs and has approximately $1.3 billion in sales. Rothblatt was interviewed by TED's Chris Anderson earlier in March to talk about her work in technology and pharmaceuticals, as well as about her life. Martine Rothblatt's journey is one of success and hard work, and her success is well-deserved. Her impact is profound and tangible. But there is something else that makes her an even more incredible force in the corporate world.
Martine Rothblatt is transgender.
However, Rothblatt's gender identity is not her only defining characteristic. Now, over ten years after her sex-reassignment surgery in 1994, Rothblatt considers herself more of a transhumanist, which was described as "a particular kind of futurist who believes that technology can liberate humans from the limits of their biology—including infertility, disease, and decay, but also, incredibly, death" in a 2014 interview with New York Magazine, after she was named the top-earning American female CEO in 2014. Her passion for technology resulted in the robot Bina48, owned by Rothblatt's Terasem Movement, in 2010. The robot, named after Rothblatt's wife of over 30 years, Bina Rothblatt, is an artificial intelligence robot that has the memories, beliefs, and feelings of Bina herself uploaded to the robot's artificial intelligence database, and is even capable of holding some conversations. 


Related Job








Internal Control Associate

Danone



              White Plains, NY, United States
            


Browse more Mogul jobs



While most of Rothblatt's work is mostly focused on her work with United Theraputics, her advancements in biotech and technology are not to be forgotten. The name Martine Rothblatt will continue to be an important one in pharmaceuticals and the corporate world in the times to come.
Check out Rothblatt's TED interview on her identity and work here.
A photo of Bina48. Credit: Hanson Robotics


